proof.p:
Take the derivative of the probability function to get 
f'(x) = \frac{\sqrt{2} {\left(\mu - x\right)} e^{\left(-\frac{{\left(\mu - x\right)}^{2}}{2 \, \sigma^{2}}\right)}}{2 \, \sqrt{\pi} \sigma^{3}}
which is zero only when x = \mu.

Take the second derivative of the probability function to get 
	f''(x) = \frac{\sqrt{2} {\left(\mu + \sigma - x\right)} {\left(\mu - \sigma - x\right)} e^{\left(-\frac{\mu^{2}}{2 \, \sigma^{2}} + \frac{\mu x}{\sigma^{2}} - \frac{x^{2}}{2 \, \sigma^{2}}\right)}}{2 \, \sqrt{\pi} \sigma^{5}}
	which is zero only when x = \mu \pm \sigma.

sage.input:
# Chi-Square Grapher
@interact
def _(r=slider(1,20,1,3,label='r =')):
    f = x^(r/2-1)*e^(-x/2)/(gamma(r/2)*2^(r/2))
    plot(f,x,0,40).show(title="Chi-Square Graph",figsize=[5,3])

proof.p:
M(0) = e^{0 \mu+\frac{1}{2}0^2\sigma^2} = e^0 = 1. Continuing, M'(t) = {\left(\sigma^2 t + \mu \right)} e^{\left(\frac{1}{2} \sigma^2 t^{2} + \mu t \right)}
and therefore M'(0) = {\left(\sigma^2 0 + \mu \right)} e^{\left(\frac{1}{2} \sigma^2 0^{2} + \mu 0 \right)} = \mu e^0 = \mu. Continuing with the second derivative, M''(t) = {\left(\sigma^2 t + \mu\right)}^2 e^{\left(\frac{1}{2} \sigma^2 t^2 + \mu t\right)} + \sigma^2 e^{\left(\frac{1}{2} \sigma^2 t^2 + \mu t\right)}
and therefore M''(0) = {\left(\sigma^2 0 + \mu\right)}^2 e^{\left(\frac{1}{2} \sigma^2 0^2 + \mu 0\right)} + \sigma^2 e^{\left(\frac{1}{2} \sigma^2 0^2 + \mu 0\right)} = \mu^2 + \sigma^2 which is the squared mean plus the variance for the normal distribution.

Using the Chi-Square probability function,
M(t) & = \int_0^{\infty} e^{tx} \frac{x^{r/2-1} e^{-x/2} }{\Gamma(r/2) 2^{r/2} } dx & = \int_0^{\infty} \frac{x^{r/2-1} e^{-x(1-2 t)/2} }{\Gamma(r/2) 2^{r/2}} dx & = \int_0^{\infty} \frac{\left ( \frac{u}{1-2t} \right )^{r/2-1} e^{-u/2} }{\Gamma(r/2) 2^{r/2} } \frac{1}{1-2t} du & = \left ( \frac{1}{1-2t} \right )^{r/2} \int_0^{\infty} \frac{u^{r/2-1} e^{-u/2} }{\Gamma(r/2) 2^{r/2}} du & = \left ( \frac{1}{1-2t} \right )^{r/2}
where the final integral is again Chi-Square and therefore has value 1.

M(0) = \left ( \frac{1}{1-2 \cdot 0} \right )^{r/2} = 1. Continuing, M'(t) = \frac{r {\left(-2 t + 1\right)}^{\frac{1}{2} r - 1}}{{\left(-2 t + 1 \right)}^{r}}
and therefore M'(0) = \frac{r {\left(-2 \cdot 0 + 1\right)}^{\frac{1}{2} r - 1}}{{\left(-2 \cdot 0 + 1 \right)}^{r}} = \frac{r}{1} = r. Continuing with the second derivative, M''(t) = -\frac{{\left(r - 2\right)} r {\left(-2 t + 1\right)}^{\frac{1}{2} r - 2}}{{\left(-2 t + 1\right)}^{r}} + \frac{2 r^{2} {\left(-2 t + 1\right)}^{r - 2}}{{\left(-2 t + 1\right)}^{\frac{3}{2} r}}
and therefore
M''(0) & = -\frac{{\left(r - 2\right)} r {\left(-2 \cdot 0 + 1\right)}^{\frac{1}{2} r - 2}}{{\left(-2 \cdot 0 + 1\right)}^{r}} + \frac{2 r^{2} {\left(-2 \cdot 0 + 1\right)}^{r - 2}}{{\left(-2 \cdot 0 + 1\right)}^{\frac{3}{2} r}} & = -\frac{{\left(r - 2\right)} r }{1} + \frac{2 r^{2} }{1}= 2r + r^2 = \sigma^2 + \mu^2
which is the squared mean plus the variance for the normal distribution.

Using the Bernoulli variables Y_k each with mean p and variance p(1-p), note that the Central Limit Theorem applied to \overline{X} = \frac{\sum Y_k}{n} gives that
\frac{\overline{X}-p}{\sqrt{p(1-p)/n}}
is approximately standard normal. By multiplying top and bottom by n yields
\frac{\sum Y_k - np}{\sqrt{np(1-p)}}
is approximately standard normal. But \sum Y_k actually is the sum of the number of successes in n trials and is therefore a Binomial variable.

Note from before that the Poisson distribution function was derived by approximating with Binomial and letting n approach infinity. Therefore, by the previous theorem, the Poisson variable is also approximately Normal using the Poisson mean and variance rather than the binomial's. Indeed, in standard units
\frac{Y - \mu}{\sqrt{\mu}}
is approximately normal for large \mu.
